<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<entry xmlns:functx="http://www.functx.com" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
    xml:id="entry_kʼ0yrma" xml:lang="os">
    <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>kʼ˳yrma</orth></form>
    <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>kʼuru</orth></form>
    <sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
            <q>глухой</q>
        </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <q>deaf</q>
        </cit></sense>
    <re><form type="lemma"><orth>bakʼ˳yrma wyn</orth></form><sense><cit type="translation"
                xml:lang="ru">
                <q>оглохнуть</q>
            </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>become deaf</q>
            </cit></sense></re>
    <cit type="exampleGroup">
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>су dissag ū, су, kæd kʼ˳yrma læg ū</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>что же удивительного (в том, что он не слышит), если он глухой</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>what is surprising (in that he cannot hear) if he is deaf</q>
            </cit>
            <bibl><ref target="#src_Коста"/><biblScope>108</biblScope></bibl>
        </cit>
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>kʼ˳yrma badæ? Axmæt kæm īs?</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>ты оглох? где Ахмат?</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>are you deaf? where is Akhmat?</q>
            </cit>
            <bibl><ref target="#src_Брит."/><biblScope>149</biblScope></bibl>
        </cit>
    </cit>
    <cit type="exampleGroup">
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>су dissag ū, су, kæd kʼ˳yrma læg ū</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>что же удивительного (в том, что он не слышит), если он глухой</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>what is surprising (in that he cannot hear) if he is deaf</q>
            </cit>
            <bibl><ref target="#src_Коста"/><biblScope>108</biblScope></bibl>
        </cit>
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>kʼ˳yrma badæ? Axmæt kæm īs?</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>ты оглох? где Ахмат?</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>are you deaf? where is Akhmat?</q>
            </cit>
            <bibl><ref target="#src_Брит."/><biblScope>149</biblScope></bibl>
        </cit>
    </cit>
    <etym xml:lang="ru">По-видимому, слово идет из кавказского субстрата. Дигорская форма %ikʼuru%i
        примыкает к <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
            ><lang/><w>qru</w><gloss><q>глухой</q></gloss></mentioned>. Для иронской формы
        %ikʼ˳yrma%i ср. <mentioned xml:lang="sva"
                ><lang/><w>qurmanǯ</w><gloss><q>глухонемой</q></gloss></mentioned>. На кавказской
        почве можно отметить еще <mentioned xml:lang="ce"><lang/><w>qʼoru</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/><w>qʼoræ</w><gloss><q>глухой</q></gloss></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="lez"><lang/><w>qürü</w><gloss><q>тупой</q></gloss></mentioned>.
        Сближение с иранской группой слов (<mentioned xml:lang="ae"
        ><lang/><w>karəna</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sog"
        ><lang/><w>*karn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ps"><lang/><w>kōn</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/><w>kar</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sgh"
                ><lang/><w>čūn</w><gloss><q>глухой</q></gloss></mentioned>) невозможно по
        фонетическим основаниям. Близость к <mentioned xml:lang="fi"
                    ><lang/><w>kuuro</w><gloss><q>глухой</q></gloss></mentioned>, если она не
        является случайной, требует своего исторического объяснения в плане осетино-финских и
        кавказско-финских лексических схождений.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">Apparently, the word comes from the Caucasian substrate. Digor form
        %ikʼuru%i sides with <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
            ><lang/><w>qru</w><gloss><q>deaf</q></gloss></mentioned>. For Iron form %ikʼ˳yrma%i cf.
            <mentioned xml:lang="sva"
            ><lang/><w>qurmanǯ</w><gloss><q>deaf-mute</q></gloss></mentioned>. See also <mentioned
            xml:lang="ce"><lang/><w>qʼoru</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang=""
                ><lang/><w>qʼoræ</w><gloss><q>deaf</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="lez"><lang/><w>qürü</w><gloss><q>blunt</q></gloss></mentioned>. The relation
        to Iranian group of words (<mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>karəna</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="sog"><lang/><w>*karn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ps"
                ><lang/><w>kōn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang=""
        ><lang/><w>kar</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sgh"
                    ><lang/><w>čūn</w><gloss><q>deaf</q></gloss></mentioned>) is impossible because
        of phonetic reasons. The closeness to <mentioned xml:lang="fi"
                    ><lang/><w>kuuro</w><gloss><q>deaf</q></gloss></mentioned>, if it is not
        accidental, needs its historical explanation from the point of view of Ossetic-Finnish and
        Caucasian-Finnish lexical convergence.</etym>
</entry>
